<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="15" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[192,675,1749,1805]" box="[192,362,1781,1805]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
(
<figureCitation box="[200,314,1781,1805]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Figures 7</figureCitation>
a-d)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[192,1440,1845,1902]" lastBlockId="16.[192,1440,1700,1853]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,480,1845,1870]" pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Description. Female.</emphasis>
Length 17.0 mm (measured from vertex to elytral apices), width 8.0 mm (measured across humeri). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[632,720,1877,1901]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="15" pageNumber="14">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
. General form elongate-ovate, moderate-sized. Integument ferrugineous to dark brown, with ochraceous and dark orange pubescence; pronotum and basal 1/2 of elytra with sparse ochraceous pubescent maculae; apical 1/2 of elytra with large, irregularly-shaped, dark orange pubescent maculae; pro- and mesosternum with gray pubescence.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="16" pageNumber="15" startId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]">
<paragraph blockId="16.[192,1440,1620,1672]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,307,1621,1643]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Figure 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Giorgi, 2001" authorityName="Giorgi" authorityYear="2001" box="[317,690,1621,1643]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Strioderes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruanus">
<emphasis box="[317,539,1621,1642]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Strioderes peruanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Giorgi, A. J." box="[548,690,1621,1643]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref11659" refString="Giorgi, A. J. 2001. A new genus and new species of Onciderini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae) from Peru. Boletim do Museu Nacional, Serie Zoologia, 471: 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="2001">Giorgi, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[703,727,1620,1642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">a)</emphasis>
Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1324,1350,1620,1642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">b)</emphasis>
Female specimen, dorsal habitus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[476,499,1649,1671]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">c)</emphasis>
Holotype male, close-up of head. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[868,892,1649,1671]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">d)</emphasis>
Female specimen, close-up of head.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[192,1440,1700,1853]" lastBlockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">
Head with frons distinctly flat, strongly transverse, about 4 times width of one lower eye lobe (as in 
<figureCitation box="[192,277,1828,1852]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Fig. 7d</figureCitation>
). Eyes with lower lobes small, ovate-oblong; eyes divided into separate upper and lower lobes, not connected by continuous row of ommatidia. Genae distinctly elongate, about 1.5 times height of lower eye lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
Antennae distinctly shorter body; antennal feebly elevated, widely separated; tubercles unarmed; scape clavate; antennomeres III strongly clavate, distinctly expanded at apical half (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1303,290,314]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
). Antennal formula based on antennomere III: scape=0.58; II=0.16; III=1; IV=0.53; V=0.31; VI=0.27; VII=0.26; VIII=0.21; IX=0.22; X=0.16; XI=0.16 (right antenna damaged, missing antennomeres VI-XI).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
Pronotum subcylindrical, strongly transverse, about 1.6 times as wide as long, sides nearly straight, without lateral protuberances (
<figureCitation box="[574,663,418,442]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
); disk entirely striated, with deep basal transverse sulcus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Scutellum transverse, apex rounded; lateral margins and center glabrous, remainder clothed in ochraceous pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
Elytra nearly 2 times as long as width at humeri (
<figureCitation box="[878,970,514,538]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="16.[192,275,1621,1643]" captionText="Figure 7. Strioderes peruanus Giorgi, 2001. a) Holotype male, dorsal habitus, with original labels. b) Female specimen, dorsal habitus. c) Holotype male, close-up of head. d) Female specimen, close-up of head." pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
), about 4.5 times as long as pronotal length, about 1.4 times broader basally than pronotum at widest; lateral margins slightly sinuate, sides feebly expanded at middle, gradually rounded to apices at apical 1/2, apices jointly rounded; basal 1/3 of elytra with dense punctation, surface coarsely, granulate-punctate, with mix of shallow and moderatelydeep punctures; humeri prominent, anterior margin arcuate, angle with moderate-sized, obtuse tubercle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Venter with procoxae large, globose, not uncate; narrowest area of prosternal process between procoxae about as wide as procoxal cavity; apex of prosternal process subtriangular. Mesosternal process about as wide as mesocoxal cavity; mesosternal process subtruncate. Fifth abdominal sternite about 2 times as long as IV, with a median triangular impression.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[192,1441,194,922]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Legs short in length; femora robust; metafemora clavate apically; tibiae slightly expanded apically; metafemora about 1/4 as long as elytra; tarsomere V about as long as I-IV combined (specimen legs damaged as follows: missing tarsi on left fore- and hindlegs; missing tarsomeres III-V on right midleg; missing right hindleg).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
